ent strategy for lowering CVC. The weakness is rxn_013: production of oleic-acid-like unsaturated C18 components directly from decanoic acid + CO + H2 is much less supported than simple saturated homolog distributions, and the network overstates certainty about specific unsaturated products.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_001\",\n        \"rxn_007\",\n        \"rxn_008\",\n        \"rxn_009\",\n        \"rxn_010\",\n        \"rxn_013\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Treat oleic acid as one possible minor long-chain co-product or exogenous amphiphile rather than a deterministic product of decanoate overgrowth\",\n        \"Preserve the mixed-amphiphile membrane logic because it directly addresses the concentration gap\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_001\": 0.05,\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.82,\n        \"rxn_003\": 0.86,\n        \"rxn_005\": 0.72,\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.6,\n        \"rxn_008\": 0.6,\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.62,\n        \"rxn_010\": 0.66,\n        \"rxn_014\": 0.9,\n        \"rxn_016\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_018\": 0.95\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.73,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.91,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.94,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.94,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.84,\n      \"feedback\": \"This pathway is highly coherent as a prebiotic systems route because it links plausible synthesis, concentration, vesicle assembly, and citrate-mediated compatibility with Mg2+-dependent chemistry. The citrate protection step is strongly literature supported. Its principal weaknesses are inherited from the upstream synthesis module rather than the downstream protocell chemistry.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_001\",\n        \"rxn_007\",\n        \"rxn_008\",\n        \"rxn_009\",\n        \"rxn_010\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Use this as the best downstream functional pathway\",\n        \"Repair the hydrothermal synthesis block to improve overall credibility\",\n        \"State explicitly that citrate solves membrane compatibility after, not during, high-temperature synthesis\"\n      ]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"best_pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n  \"overall_confidence\": 0.79,\n  \"network_feedback\": \"The network is topologically good and captures the correct systems-level story from the literature: hydrothermal/subsurface generation of reducing power and C1 feedstocks, Fe/Ni-catalyzed FTT production of a homologous fatty-acid series including decanoic acid, transport to surface environments for concentration, and final assembly of mixed amphiphile vesicles in prebiotic settings. It also correctly emphasizes that pure decanoic acid is concentration-limited and that mixed amphiphile systems solve much of the membrane-formation problem. However, the network falls short of approval because several reaction nodes are chemically or mechanistically overstated. The most serious defect is rxn_001, which incorrectly writes hydrogen generation as CO2 -> H2. A second major issue is the repeated representation of FTT chain growth as a literal sequence of free-acid elongations (acetate -> butyrate -> hexanoate -> octanoate -> decanoate). Literature supports distributed surface-catalyzed product series, not these isolated conversions. A third issue is that some specific products, especially oleic-acid-like unsaturated components and monoglyceride formation, are less directly supported than the network implies. On literature alignment, the network is partly strong: it uses the correct dominant route class (FTT), recognizes the central importance of CO/formate over dissolved CO2, and includes transport/concentration and mixed-amphiphile assembly consistent with Budin, Jordan, Hanczyc, and Adamala/Szostak. But it does not fully respect the exact experimental framing that C10 is produced as part of a