in serpentinizing systems"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-surface reduction of CO2 by H2 yields formate/formic acid as a C1 intermediate more reactive than dissolved CO2 for later FTT-related chemistry.", "reasoning": "Formate is a key hydrothermal C1 intermediate and likely bridge between CO2-rich geochemistry and more reactive carbonyl feedstocks; Lost City fluids contain formate, while iron-sulfur minerals can activate CO2 even if long-chain synthesis is not demonstrated on them directly (Proskurowski et al., 2008; Santos-Carballal et al., 2018; McCollom & Seewald, 2001)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Hydrothermal generation of oxalic acid from reduced C1 chemistry", "inputs": ["mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_005"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS2)", "greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-450K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "pyrite (FeS2), greigite (Fe3S4)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "speculative connector using reduced hydrothermal C1 chemistry to link formate pools to oxalate/formate FTT feed systems"}, "mechanism": "C1 carboxyl species undergo surface-mediated coupling/oxidation-state reorganization to produce dicarboxylate feedstocks relevant to later thermal decomposition chemistry.", "reasoning": "Oxalic acid was used directly as an experimentally validated FTT precursor in stainless-steel reactors, but its prebiotic sourcing is less constrained. This node is therefore included as a necessary but speculative connector to integrate the McCollom precursor system into a connected network (McCollom et al., 1999)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Thermal decomposition of formic acid to CO feedstock", "inputs": ["mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_004"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["elemental iron (Fe0)", "magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "423-523K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "elemental iron (Fe0), magnetite (Fe3O4)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "subsurface or post-impact hydrothermal conditions; CO-generating intermediates favored over dissolved CO2 as FTT feed"}, "mechanism": "Formic acid thermally decomposes on metallic/oxide surfaces to generate CO, providing the kinetically necessary carbonyl substrate for FTT chain growth.", "reasoning": "The literature emphasizes that CO or CO-generating intermediates, not dissolved CO2 alone, are the effective feedstocks for abiotic FTT lipid synthesis. Formic acid is a validated precursor in aqueous FTT experiments (McCollom et al., 1999; McCollom et al., 2010; Rushdi & Simoneit, 2001)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Thermal decomposition of oxalic acid to CO feedstock", "inputs": ["mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_004"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["elemental iron (Fe0)", "magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "423-523K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "elemental iron (Fe0), magnetite (Fe3O4)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "subsurface or post-impact hydrothermal conditions; oxalic acid serves as a CO-generating precursor in steel-catalyzed lipid synthesis experiments"}, "mechanism": "Oxalic acid decomposes thermally to carbonyl fragments including CO, enriching the reactive feedstock pool for surface-mediated FTT chemistry.", "reasoning": "Oxalic acid was one of the specific precursors used in the landmark aqueous abiotic lipid synthesis experiments that produced homologous acids up to >C35 (McCollom et al., 1999; Rushdi & Simoneit, 2001)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Aqueous Fe-Ni-catalyzed Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of homologous amphiphiles", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_006", "mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_011"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["elemental iron (Fe0)", "magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "423-523K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "Fe-Ni-Cr metallic surfaces approximated here by elemental iron (Fe0) with magnetite (Fe3O4)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "150-250C optimum equivalent; 2-3 days; homologous ASF-like product distribution of acids, alcohols, hydrocarbons and ketones"}, "mechanism": "Surface-bound carbonyl species undergo sequential CO insertion and hydrogenation on Fe/Ni-bearing metallic surfaces, yielding a homologous mixture of n-alkanoic acids and related amphiphiles including decanoic acid.", "reasoning": "This is the strongest experimentally supported route to prebiotic decanoic acid. McCollom et al. produced C2 to >C35 lipids from formic/oxalic acid in steel reactors at 175C over 2-3 days, and Rushdi & Simoneit found highest acid yields at 150-250C. The network deliberately represents homologous-distribution production rather than unsupported deterministic free-acid elongation (McCollom et al., 1999; Rushdi & Simoneit, 2001)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Gas-phase meteoritic-iron FTT synthesis peaking at C9-C10", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_011"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["elemental iron (Fe0)", "magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "673K", "pressure": "moderate-high", "catalyst": "meteoritic iron analogue; K2CO3-promoted Fe surface chemistry approximated with elemental iron (Fe0)", "aqueous": "false", "other": "CO:D2/H2 about 1:1; 24-48 h; post-impact or gas-solid reactor analogue; distribution peaks at C9-C10"}, "mechanism": "Gas-phase FTT chain growth on meteoritic/native iron forms a unimodal medium-chain fatty-acid distribution with strong production near decanoic acid.", "reasoning": "Nooner and Oro directly produced saturated fatty acids from C5-C18 with a peak at C9-C10 using Canyon Diablo meteoritic iron at 400C for 24-48 h. This is the most direct experimental support for decanoic acid-favored abiotic synthesis (Nooner & Oro, 1979)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Post-impact global FTT generation of fatty-acid mixtures on iron-rich surfaces", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_006", "mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_011"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["elemental iron (Fe0)", "magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": ">373K", "pressure": "variable", "catalyst": "iron-rich post-impact surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "reducing post-impact atmosphere containing H2, CO, CO2; synthesis sustained over long cooling intervals"}, "mechanism": "Impact-generated reducing atmospheres and iron-rich hot surfaces operate as large-scale FTT reactors, producing total fatty-acid inventories far exceeding other sources.", "reasoning": "Cohen et al. quantitatively concluded that post-impact FTT synthesis on iron-rich surfaces could outproduce meteoritic delivery or spark-discharge sources by about 100-fold in total fatty-acid mass, making it a major plausible source of decanoic acid-bearing mixtures (Cohen et al., 2023)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Exogenous delivery of meteoritic fatty acid mixture", "inputs": [], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "borate minerals"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite (clay), borate minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "delivery to surface pools; physical influx rather than in situ synthesis; medium-chain monocarboxylic acids present at trace levels up to C12"}, "mechanism": "Meteorite infall supplies preformed fatty-acid mixtures, which are then retained and processed in surface depositional environments.", "reasoning": "Meteorites contain monocarboxylic acids from C2 to C12 and can deliver C10-containing mixtures, though alone they are generally insufficient to exceed vesicle-forming concentrations. This is modeled correctly as exogenous input, not chain elongation from shorter acids (Yuen & Kvenvolden, 1973; Lawless & Yuen, 1979; Huang et al., 2005; Pearce et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Exogenous UV-ice photoproduct amphiphile delivery", "inputs": [], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 